I will caution against using two arrays. You should create a new class for the starts and ends. It will look like this.

```
class OrderedPair implements Comparable&lt;OrderedPair&gt; {
    public int start;
    public int end;
    public OrderedPair(int start, int end) {
      this.start = start;
      this.end = end;
    }
    public int compareTo(OrderedPair other) {
      if (this.start &gt; other.start) {
        return 1;
      } else if (this.start &lt; other.start) {
        return -1;
      } else {
        return 0;
      }
    }
  }
```
Then I would replace most code in main with the following. 
```
ArrayList&lt;OrderedPair&gt; pairs = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
  pairs.add(new OrderedPair(scanner.nextInt(), scanner.nextInt()));
}
Collections.sort(pairs);
List&lt;Integer&gt; list = coordinates(n, pairs);
```
Obviously, this will require other changes to the code. You will have to change the coordinates() function. But it will have much better runtime, compared to the selection sort you are running now.

